Europe
------
[1] UK (Bolton)
Date: Sat 29 Dec 2012
Source: The Bolton News [edited]
http://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/local/10131465.Town___s_highest_number_of_measles_cases_in_12_years/?ref=nt


There have been 62 cases of measles in Bolton this year [2012] compared to just one last year.

Parents are being urged to make sure their children have had the MMR jab to protect them against the disease. Most of the children affected are babies under the age of 12 months, who are too young to have had the jabs, and youngsters aged about 11 to 14, whose parents decided not to get their children immunised after controversial research was published which claimed to link the MMR jab with autism.

In early December [2012], Harper Green Secondary School and a private nursery in Bromley Cross were hit by a measles outbreak affecting more than 30 children. Since then, there have been cases across Bolton.

Measles can cause lifelong problems and disabilities and in some cases can kill. It can lead to serious conditions including bronchitis, pneumonia, convulsions, encephalitis, which is swelling of the brain, and meningitis. Health protection specialist Graham Munslow, from NHS [National Health Service] Bolton, said it was the highest number of cases in Bolton in more than 12 years. He has urged parents to get their children vaccinated. He said: "It is not like chicken pox; measles is much more damaging to children."

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
