The Americas
-----------
[5] Canada (QC): super-spreading event
Date: Wed 26 Dec 2012
Surce: CIDRAP News [edited]
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/cidrap/content/other/news/dec2612newsscan.html


Despite very high measles immunization coverage in Quebec, the province was the site in 2011 of the largest measles outbreak in North America in the past decade. A study of the outbreak, published online in the Journal of Infectious Diseases on 21 Dec 2012 [Reference and Abstract below], found an unexpected vulnerability to illness even in recipients of a 2-dose vaccination regimen. Confirmed cases in the outbreak numbered 725, with 678 of them resulting from one super-spreading importation. The index case-patient in this importation was an adult who had traveled to the Caribbean in the spring, spending several hours at the Montreal airport. This person, who had received one dose of vaccine, worked in a high school; secondary infections spread over a period of 26 weeks. Overall, adolescents aged 12 to 17 years made up 56 percent of the cases in Quebec. Among patients in this age-group, 22 percent had received 2 doses of vaccine; illness was milder and was associated with a significantly lower risk of hospitalization in these patients compared with unvaccinated patients and those who had received just one dose. The authors state that the Quebec epidemic "provides an opportunity for jurisdictions with a stated goal of measles elimination to reflect both on the very [high] levels of population immunity required and how tenuous these levels may be."

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[A ProMED-mail HealthMap for Quebec, Canada can be found at http://healthmap.org/r/1*Eh.

The reference and abstract for the publication referred to above are the following:

Title: The largest measles epidemic in North America in a decade -- Quebec, Canada, 2011: Contribution of susceptibility, serendipity and super-spreading events on elimination. By Gaston De Serres and 11 others. In The Journal of Infectious Diseases, Advance Access, 10.1093/infdis/jis92 [edited] http://jid.oxfordjournals.org/content/early/2012/12/19/infdis.jis923.short.

"Introduction: We describe the largest measles epidemic in North America in the last decade occurring in the population of Quebec, Canada in 2011 where one- and 2-dose vaccine coverage among children 3 years of age were 95-97 percent and 90 percent, respectively, with 3-5 percent unvaccinated.

Methods: Cases identified through passive surveillance and outbreak investigation were contacted to describe clinical course, vaccination status and possible source of infection.

Results: There were 21 measles importations and 725 cases. A super-spreading event triggered by one importation resulted in sustained transmission and 678 cases. The incidence per 100 000 was 9.1, highest in adolescents 12-17 years old (75.6) comprising 56 percent of cases. Among adolescent cases, 22 percent had received 2 vaccine doses. Outbreak investigation showed this proportion to have been an under-estimate: active case-finding identified 130 percent more cases among 2-dose recipients. Two-dose recipients had milder illness and significantly lower risk of hospitalization compared to unvaccinated or single-dose cases.

Conclusion: A chance super-spreading event revealed an overall level of immunity barely above the elimination threshold when taking into account unexpected vulnerability in 2-dose recipients. Unvaccinated individuals remain the immunization priority, but a better understanding of susceptibility in 2-dose recipients is needed to define effective interventions if elimination is to be achieved."

It will be relevant to determine whether the super-spreader event was related to the specific genotype of the imported virus or to the immune responses of those susceptible to infection. For a review, see: The genetic basis for inter-individual immune response variation to measles vaccine: new understanding and new vaccine approaches. Haralambieva IH et al., Expert Rev Vaccines. 2013 Jan;12(1):57-70. doi: 10.1586/erv.12.134.

The authors of this review reason that the live-attenuated measles vaccine is effective, but measles outbreaks still occur in vaccinated populations. This warrants elucidation of the determinants of measles vaccine-induced protective immunity. Inter-individual variability in markers of measles vaccine-induced immunity, including neutralizing antibody levels, is regulated in part by host genetic factor variations. There have been recent advances in understanding measles vaccine immunogenetics relative to the perspective of developing better measles vaccines. Important genetic regulators of measles vaccine-induced immunity, such as HLA class I and HLA class II genotypes, single nucleotide polymorphisms in cytokine/cytokine receptor genes (IL12B, IL12RB1, IL2, IL10), and the cell surface measles virus receptor CD46 gene, have been identified and independently replicated. These observations may help explain a variety of immune response-related phenotypes and promote a new paradigm of "vaccinomics" for novel vaccine development. - Mod.CP]
